The debate about whether respirators are more effective than MMs at preventing respiratory infections, in particular influenza, will continue. There is a growing body of evidence to suggest that the aerosol route of infection could be significant;
24
 if we could identify the circumstances in which this becomes likely, then a respirator should have a place. However, until we are able to do this reliably or conduct a trial large enough to capture a high event rate, a proportion of which are generated by aerosol‐mediated transmissions, we are unlikely to be able to conclude from RCTs that respirators are superior for all situations.
